      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fields of Oil, From Iraq to Alaska</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Richard Wolfson letter says modest conservation effort in United States would balance out Iraqi oil embargo (Apr 10 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Missing Energy Strategy'' (editorial, April 10) says that ''spare oil capacity in the system'' will prevent Iraq's oil embargo from creating a shortage in the United States. That may be true, but do we really want to rely on the good graces of ''the system'' to save us from Saddam Hussein? How much better it would be if we as individuals and as a nation decided that we just didn't need Iraqi oil.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Missing Energy Strategy'' (editorial, April 10) says that ''spare oil capacity in the system'' will prevent Iraq's oil embargo from creating a shortage in the United States. That may be true, but do we really want to rely on the good graces of ''the system'' to save us from Saddam Hussein? How much better it would be if we as individuals and as a nation decided that we just didn't need Iraqi oil.</p>
        <p>A modest change in our driving habits is all it would take to reduce oil consumption by the small percentage that Iraq now supplies. That change might even mark the beginning of a serious effort to reduce our dependence on imported oil and our environmentally unsound addiction to fossil fuels.</p>
        <p>RICHARD WOLFSON  Weybridge, Vt., April 10, 2002</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of physics and environmental studies, Middlebury College.</p>
      </block>
